I. Basic 2D Graphs

The plot command is used to create two-dimensional plots. The base format of the command is plot(x,y) where x and y are vectors. The two vectors must have the same number of elements. The curve is constructed of straight-line segments that connect the points whose coordinates are defined by the elements of the vectors x and y.
Let's assume we were given the data for x, y:
We want to create a simple cartesian plot of each (x,y) pairs
x = [1,2,3,5,7,7.5,8,10];
y = [2, 6.5, 7, 7 5.5 4 6 8];
plot(x,y)
The line(x,y) is similar to plot(x,y) but does it can't be used with the formatting commands as we will see later.
line(x,y)
Note: if you are coding in the script editor you will get the plotted figures in a separate window like this
Line formatting in the plot command are used by putting the specifiers within single quotation marks
plot(x,y,'--')
figure
plot(x,y,'k*-.')
Figure formatting:
Some of the common figure commands are:
  • xlabel(The x axis): gives label to the x axis
  • ylabel(The y label): gives label to the y axis
  • title(The title): gives title to the figure
  • axis([xmin xmax ymin ymax]): determines the maximum and minimum limits of the figure in both x and y axises
  • grid on: adds grids to the plot
  • legend('my plot'): adds an explanatory table for the plot using the used specifiers
plot(x,y,'r+:')
xlabel('x data');
ylabel('y data');
title('Demo Title');
axis([-1 11 0 10])
grid on
legend('our graph')
Plotting more than one line in a single figure
To do that we either use the hold on command which overlaps the latest plot being excuted with an existing plot, or we just put all lines in a single plot command.
In the following segement we will plot with the (x,y) pairs a new line of (x2,y2) pairs constructed as shown below:
x2 = x ;
y2 = y + 2;
plot(x,y,'b*-.')
hold on
plot(x2,y2,'r*-')
title('mutliple plots using the hold on command ')
legend ('first line' , 'shifted')
hold off
Note: remember to close off the hold command or later plots will be merged with the current figure.
figure
plot(x,y,'b*-.', x2, y2 ,'r*-')
title('mutliple plots using a single plot command')
legend ('original' , 'shifted')
grid on

II. Classification of Signals

  • Continuous-Time Signals: Most signals in the real world are continuous time, as the scale is infinitesimally fine. such voltage, velocity. Denoted by x(t), where the time interval may be bounded (finite) or infinite.
  • Discrete-Time Signals (Sampled CT signal): Some real world and many digital signals are discrete time, as they are sampled. such as pixels, or anything that a digital computer processes. Denoted by x[n], where n is an integer value that varies discretely.
  • Digital Signals: is a signal that takes on only a discrete set of values.

III. Signal Representation in Matlab

  • If data is given, either from a tabular file or recorded from a sensor, the information is stored elements of the vectors such t, x and y (or any valid variable name)
  • If the values of the signal are determined by a function of time , a vector t is created first, then the values of are calculated for each value of t. The spacing (difference) between the elements of t must be such that the plotted curve will show the details of the function.
Examples of common signal functions, such trigonometric functions, square, unit step, sawtooth, sinc, exponential function, etc..

IV. Construction of Common Signals in Matlab

4.1. Sinusoidal Functions

Continuous-time signal representation. Time (the independent variable t) is defined by using a very small step (time step e.g: 0.01) in the continuous domain between a bounded time interval to , then dependent variable y(t) is defined in the continuous set of values as a function of t. We use the plot command to visualize such representation.
close all % closes all pervious figures
t = 0:0.01:10; % the independent variable, time
y1 = sin(4*pi*t); % the dependent variable
y2 = cos(t);
plot(t,y1,'r',t,y2,'b')
title('CT sine & cos signals')
legend('sin','cos')
grid on
Discrete-time signal representation. in a simialr way to the CT representation, the independent variable, say n is first defined, and the dependent variable is calculated for every step in n. Note that the command stem is used instead of plot to visualize the DT representation.
figure
n = 0:0.01:2;
g1 = sin(2*pi*n);
g2 = cos(2*pi*n);
stem(n,g1,'r')
hold on
stem(n,g2,'b')
title('DT sine & cos signals ')
legend('sin','cos')
grid on

4.2. The Exponential Function

The exponential signal represents an exponentially increasing or falling series. If we denote if a > 0 then it's an increasing function, whereas if a < 0 then its a decreasing function.
Example
Plot the signals and in the time interval .
close all
t = -2 : 0.01 : 5 ;
y1 = 3 * exp(0.4 * t);
y2 = exp(-0.9 * t ) ;
plot(t,y1,'r-.',t,y2 , 'b:')
title('Exp function')
Undefined function or variable 'g'.

4.3. Square and Sawtooth Signals: using subplot

Creating Subplots. Multiple plots can be created on the same page with the subplot command, which has the form: subplot(m,n,p). The command divides the Figure Window into (m rows) x (n columns) rectangular subplots. p is the index for area where the next plot will take place. Note that each subplot can have its own title, labels, legend, etc..
t = 0 : 0.01 : 10;
sqr = square(2*pi*t);
swth = sawtooth(2*pi*t);
subplot(2,1,1)
plot(t,sqr)
axis([0 10 0 1.2 ])
title('square signal')
subplot(2,1,2)
plot(t,swth)
title('sawtooth signal')
grid on

4.4. Unit Step Function:

This function denoted by is used for signals that start at , it has the value of zero for negative arguments and one for postive arguments.
The heaviside command is used to create the unit-step function in Matlab
t = -4 : 0.01 : 10 ;
y = heaviside(t);
figure
plot(t,y);
grid on;
title('Unit-step function');
axis([-4 8 -0.2 1.2 ])

4.5. Pulse generation:

A pulse is a type of signal in which a rapid, transient change in the amplitude from a baseline value to a higher or lower value, followed by a rapid return to the baseline value.
Common pulse types:
  • Rectangular Pulse
  • Triangular Pulse
  • Unit Impulse
t = -0.1 : 0.01 : 0.1 ;
tri_puls = tripuls(t,20e-3);
sqr_puls = rectpuls(t,20e-3);
subplot(2,1,1)
plot(t,tri_puls) ; title('Triangular pulse') ;
subplot(2,1,2) ;
plot(t,sqr_puls); title('Rectangular pulse');
